The '''2009 UEFA Champions League Final''' was played on 27 May 2009 at the [[Stadio Olimpico]] in [[Rome]], [[Italy]]. The match determined the winners of the [[2008<U+2013>09 UEFA Champions League|2008<U+2013>09 season]] of the [[UEFA Champions League]], a tournament for the top [[association football|football]] clubs in Europe. The match was won by [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] of [[Spain]], who beat [[England]]'s [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] 2<U+2013>0. [[Samuel Eto'o]] opened the scoring in the 10th&nbsp;minute, and [[Lionel Messi]] added another goal 20&nbsp;minutes from the end to earn Barcelona an historic [[Treble (association football)#Continental trebles|treble]] of [[La Liga]], the [[Copa del Rey]] and the Champions League, a feat never before achieved by a Spanish club.<ref name="guardiola_salutes">{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=Ashby |title=Guardiola salutes his treble winners |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15280/match=302813/report=rw.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=27 May 2009 |accessdate=28 May 2009 }}</ref> The match was refereed by [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[referee (association football)|referee]] [[Massimo Busacca]].<ref name="referee"/>

This was Barcelona's third victory in the competition, 17 years after they first won the European Cup in [[1992 European Cup Final|1992]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Haslam |title=Spain savour European pre-eminence |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=833250.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=27 May 2009 |accessdate=28 May 2009 }}</ref> Manchester United went into the match as the competition's defending champions, the first defending champions to reach the final since [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in [[1997 UEFA Champions League Final|1997]]. Manchester United also sought to be the first team to retain the European Cup since [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] in [[1990 European Cup Final|1990]]. It was the fifth year in a row in which the final involved at least one [[England|English]] team.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rome ready to welcome European superpowers |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15280/match=302813/report=mb.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=26 May 2009 |accessdate=28 May 2009 }}</ref> The Stadio Olimpico had hosted three previous Champions League finals, following the [[1977 European Cup Final|1977]], [[1984 European Cup Final|1984]] and [[1996 UEFA Champions League Final|1996]] matches.<ref name="olimpico"/>

As winners of the 2008<U+2013>09 Champions League, Barcelona later played against [[2008<U+2013>09 UEFA Cup]] winners [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]] in the [[2009 UEFA Super Cup]],<ref name="super_cup">{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Haslam |title=Pedro pounces to add to Bar<U+00E7>a glory |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/supercup/fixturesresults/round=2000023/match=2001219/report=rp.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=28 August 2009 |accessdate=8 September 2009 }}</ref> and they will represent UEFA at the [[2009 FIFA Club World Cup]].<ref name="club_world_cup">{{cite news |title=Club elite take shape |url=http://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/news/newsid=1083350.html |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de Football Association |date=22 July 2009 |accessdate=26 July 2009 }}</ref> Despite winning the Champions League final, Barcelona won [[Euro|<U+20AC>]]8&nbsp;million less prize money than Manchester United.<ref name="distribution">{{cite journal |year=2009 |month=July |title=Distribution of revenue to participating clubs |journal=uefadirect |issue=87 |pages=6<U+2013>7 |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |url=http://www.uefa.com/multimediafiles/download/publications/uefa/uefamedia/83/97/47/839747_download.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=26 July 2009 }}</ref>
{{TOClimit}}

==Background==
Manchester United and Barcelona had previously faced each other nine times in European competitions: three times in the [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] and six times in the UEFA Champions League. Of those nine matches, Manchester United had recorded three wins to Barcelona's two, with the remaining four matches finishing in draws. The only time that the two teams met in a final came in 1991, when they contested the [[1991 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1991 Cup Winners' Cup final]]. The first meeting between the two sides came in the third round of the [[European Cup Winners' Cup 1983<U+2013>84|1983<U+2013>84 Cup Winners' Cup]]; Barcelona won the first leg at the [[Camp Nou]] 2<U+2013>0, but Manchester United won the return leg 3<U+2013>0 at [[Old Trafford]] to reach the semi-finals. That result marked Manchester United's biggest win over Barcelona; Barcelona's biggest win was a 4<U+2013>0 home victory in the group stage of the [[1994<U+2013>95 UEFA Champions League|1994<U+2013>95 Champions League]]. The most recent meeting between the teams came in the semi-finals of the [[2007<U+2013>08 UEFA Champions League|2007<U+2013>08 Champions League]], when United held Barcelona to a 0<U+2013>0 draw at the Camp Nou before beating them 1<U+2013>0 back at Old Trafford.<ref>{{cite web |title=United versus Barcelona |url=http://www.stretfordend.co.uk/opponents/barcelona.html |publisher=StretfordEnd.co.uk |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref>

[[File:Trophy in Rome.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=The silver European Champions Clubs' Cup stands in a clear display case in front of the Colosseum|The [[European Champion Clubs' Cup]] on display outside the [[Colosseum]]]]
Both teams went into the match as the champions of their respective countries <U+2013> the first time that the final had been contested by domestic champions since [[1999 UEFA Champions League Final|1999]], when Manchester United beat [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] 2<U+2013>1 at Barcelona's home, the Camp Nou <U+2013> both winning with games to spare. Manchester United won their 11th [[Premier League]] title with a 0<U+2013>0 draw at home to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 16 May,<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Man Utd 0-0 Arsenal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8038259.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=16 May 2009 |accessdate=17 May 2009 }}</ref> while Barcelona were confirmed as [[La Liga]] champions for the first time in three years when [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] lost to [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] on the same day.<ref name="spanish_title">{{cite news |title=Barca clinch Spanish league title |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8054011.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=16 May 2009 |accessdate=17 May 2009 }}</ref> Both Manchester United and Barcelona were also looking for another Champions League title to cap a season in which they had won multiple trophies: Manchester United had already won four out of a possible seven trophies in [[Manchester United F.C. season 2008<U+2013>09|2008<U+2013>09]] and were playing for the possibility of becoming the third team to retain the [[The Double#European Double|European Double]] (the domestic league and the European Cup), while Barcelona were aiming to become the first Spanish club to win a [[Treble (association football)#Continental trebles|Treble]] of [[La Liga 2008<U+2013>09|La Liga]], the [[Copa del Rey 2008<U+2013>09|Copa del Rey]] and the UEFA Champions League.<ref name="spanish_title"/>

[[File:Stadio Olimpico 2009.jpg|thumb|left|alt=The fa<U+00E7>ade of the Stadio Olimpico in Rome is draped with banners for the 2009 Champions League final.|The [[Stadio Olimpico]] had hosted three European Cup finals before 2009.]]
The [[Stadio Olimpico]] in [[Rome]] had hosted three [[List of European Cup and UEFA Champions League winners|European Cup finals]] before 2009: the [[1977 European Cup Final|1977]] and [[1984 European Cup Final|1984 finals]], both of which were won by [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] <U+2013> Liverpool beat [[Borussia M<U+00F6>nchengladbach]] 3<U+2013>1 in 1977 before beating home side [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] 4<U+2013>2 on [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalties]] after the match finished 1<U+2013>1 after extra time; the most recent final to be held at the Stadio Olimpico was the [[1996 UEFA Champions League Final|1996 final]], which [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] also won 4<U+2013>2 on penalties after a 1<U+2013>1 draw with [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Eugene |last=Ravdin |coauthors=Menicucci, Paolo |title=Moscow and Rome feast on finals |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=464251.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |location=Riga & Milan |date=5 October 2006 |accessdate=12 May 2009 }}</ref>

The construction of the stadium was commissioned by Italian dictator [[Benito Mussolini]] in the mid-1930s as the centrepiece of a new sports complex in the city, to be named ''Foro Mussolini''. After the [[World War II|Second World War]], the complex was renamed ''Foro Italico'' and the stadium was radically redesigned as a 54,000-capacity arena for the [[1960 Summer Olympics]]. After hosting the [[1987 World Championships in Athletics|1987 World Athletics Championships]], the stadium was redeveloped in time for the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]], at which [[Germany national football team|West Germany]]'s 1<U+2013>0 win over [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] in the [[1990 FIFA World Cup Final|final]] was played there. The stadium's most recent renovation, in 2008, increased its capacity to 72,689.<ref name="olimpico"/>
{{-}}

