===Barcelona===
[[File:Wisla Krakow v Barcelona 2008-08-26.jpg|thumb|alt=A photograph from behind the goal shows Barcelona and Wis<U+0142>a Krak<U+00F3>w players gathering in the near penalty area for a corner kick. Wis<U+0142>a Krak<U+00F3>w players are standing closer to the goal, and the referee is standing on the edge of the penalty area.|Barcelona's players prepare to attack a corner in the second leg of their third qualifying round tie against [[Wis<U+0142>a Krak<U+00F3>w]].]]
By virtue of their third-place finish in the [[La Liga 2007<U+2013>08|2007<U+2013>08 Primera Division]], Barcelona entered the 2008<U+2013>09 Champions League at the third qualifying round stage. Based on their [[UEFA coefficient#Club coefficient|UEFA coefficient]], Barcelona were seeded for the third qualifying round draw,<ref>{{cite news |title=Continental powers to learn fate |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=735566.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=31 July 2008 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref> and drawn against [[Ekstraklasa 2007-08|Polish champions]] [[Wis<U+0142>a Krak<U+00F3>w]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Schalke-Atl<U+00E9>tico pick of the draw |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=735569.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=1 August 2008 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref> A 4<U+2013>0 win in the first leg at the [[Camp Nou]] made defeat in the second leg immaterial and Barcelona were entered into the group stage draw.<ref>{{cite news |first=Delf<U+00ED>n |last=Ram<U+00ED>rez |title=Brilliant Bar<U+00E7>a sweep Wis<U+0142>a aside |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15275/match=303817/report=rp.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=13 August 2008 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Luciano |last=Mera |title=Cl<U+00E9>ber rouses Wis<U+0142>a but Bar<U+00E7>a pass test |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15275/match=303833/report=rp.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=26 August 2008 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref>

Barcelona's UEFA coefficient placed them in the top eight seeds for the draw, meaning that they would avoid having to play against [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] or holders and their semi-final opponents from 2007<U+2013>08 [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. However, they could still draw [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] or [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Europe's finest set for group stage draw |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=740905.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=28 August 2008 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref> In the end, Barcelona were drawn into Group C against [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]], [[FC Basel|Basel]] and [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Hard work ahead for Laporta's Bar<U+00E7>a |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=743396.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=28 August 2008 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref>

Four wins and a draw at home to Basel placed Barcelona on top of their group with a game to spare, and despite defeat to Shakhtar Donetsk on Matchday 6, they still had the third-best record amongst the qualifiers for the first knockout round.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andy |last=Brassell |title=Breathtaking Bar<U+00E7>a continue goal glut |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15276/match=302758/report=rp.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=26 November 2008 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref> As group winners, Barcelona would avoid being drawn with other group winners, including Manchester United, Liverpool, Juventus and Bayern Munich, but they could still be drawn against runners-up such as Chelsea, Internazionale and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Europe awaits UEFA Champions League draw |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=787334.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=19 December 2008 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref> The draw eventually paired them with [[Olympique Lyonnais]] and, as group winners, they were given the right to play the second leg at home.<ref>{{cite news |title=Holders United to take on Inter |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=788360.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=19 December 2008 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref>

In the first leg in [[Lyon]], Barcelona fell behind to a seventh-minute free kick from [[Juninho Pernambucano]], only for [[Thierry Henry]] to equalise half-way through the second half, giving Barcelona an [[away goals rule|away goal]] to take back to the Camp Nou.<ref>{{cite news |first=Matthew |last=Spiro |title=Henry header brings Bar<U+00E7>a reward |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15277/match=302789/report=rp.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=24 February 2009 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref> They needed a win or a no-score draw to guarantee passage, but a 4<U+2013>1 half-time lead set the stage for a convincing 5<U+2013>2 win. Two first-half goals from Henry and one each from [[Lionel Messi]] and [[Samuel Eto'o]] were followed by goals from [[Jean Makoun]] and Juninho either side of the interval to reduce Lyon's deficit. However, a goal from [[Seydou Keita (footballer)|Seydou Keita]] in the fifth&nbsp;minute of injury time secured a 6<U+2013>3 aggregate win and passage to the next round.<ref>{{cite news |first=Graham |last=Hunter |title=First-half flurry seals Bar<U+00E7>a passage |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15277/match=302793/report=rp.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=11 March 2009 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref>

In the quarter-finals, Barcelona were drawn against their fellow leading-scorers in the competition, Bayern Munich, who had beaten Barcelona's group stage opposition, Sporting CP, 12<U+2013>1 on aggregate in the previous round.<ref>{{cite news |title=English teams dominate draw lineup |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=809373.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=20 March 2009 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref><ref name="draw">{{cite news |title=Porto placed in United's path |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=811234.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=20 March 2009 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref> However, despite Bayern's impressive scoring record, goals from Messi and Eto'o gave Barcelona a 2<U+2013>0 lead within the first 12&nbsp;minutes. Messi and Henry also scored to seal a 4<U+2013>0 home victory before half-time.<ref>{{cite news |first=Graham |last=Turner |title=Bar<U+00E7>a brilliance turns tables on Bayern |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15278/match=302804/report=rp.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=8 April 2009 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref> The lack of an away goal meant that Bayern Munich would have to win by five clear goals to qualify for the semi-finals; after a goalless first half, they took the lead through [[Franck Rib<U+00E9>ry]] in the 47th&nbsp;minute, but it was not enough for Bayern as Keita equalised in the 73rd&nbsp;minute to clinch a 5<U+2013>1 aggregate win for the Spanish side.<ref>{{cite news |first=Gavin |last=Jackson |title=Bayern save face as Barcelona keep apace |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15278/match=302806/report=rp.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=14 April 2009 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref>

[[File:CHELSEA (1) v (1) barcelona.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Chelsea (blue) and Barcelona players (yellow) leave the pitch at the end of the first half of their semi-final second leg at Stamford Bridge. The referee is talking to two Barcelona players.|Barcelona take on [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] in the semi-final second leg.]]
The quarter-final draw also determined the teams' routes to the final, with Barcelona facing the prospect of meeting either Chelsea or Liverpool in the semi-finals.<ref name="draw"/> After a 3<U+2013>1 win at [[Anfield]],<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Liverpool 1-3 Chelsea |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7977013.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=8 April 2009 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref> Chelsea qualified for the semi-finals with a 4<U+2013>4 draw at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Fletcher |title=Chelsea 4-4 Liverpool (agg: 7-5) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7977038.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=14 April 2009 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref> The semi-final first leg was played at the Camp Nou; although Barcelona enjoyed the majority of the possession, Chelsea's defence was resolute and they became the first side to keep a clean sheet in Barcelona in this season's competition, coming away with a goalless draw.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Stevenson |title=Barcelona 0-0 Chelsea |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8010833.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=28 April 2009 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref> Barcelona needed to avoid defeat to reach the final, but they found themselves a goal down within 10 minutes; after they failed to clear [[Frank Lampard]]'s pass into the penalty area, [[Michael Essien]] fired a left-footed volley past [[V<U+00ED>ctor Vald<U+00E9>s]] into the roof of the net. The rest of the match continued much the same as the first leg, with Barcelona retaining most of the possession. Despite this, they found themselves guilty of several fouls, while Chelsea made four unsuccessful penalty appeals during the match. Meanwhile, [[Daniel Alves]] received his third yellow card of the knockout stage, ruling him out of Barcelona's next match, and [[<U+00C9>ric Abidal]] was given a straight red card for a foul on [[Nicolas Anelka]] as the French [[forward (association football)|forward]] was through on goal. However, television replays after the incident appeared to show that Anelka tripped over his own feet. Norwegian referee [[Tom Henning <U+00D8>vreb<U+00F8>]] allowed a minimum of four&nbsp;minutes of injury time at the end of the second half; in the third of those four&nbsp;minutes <U+2013> just when it looked like Chelsea were about to secure a repeat of the [[2008 UEFA Champions League Final|2008 final]] <U+2013> Messi played the ball across the edge of the penalty area to [[Andr<U+00E9>s Iniesta]], who shot just past [[Petr <U+010C>ech]]'s outstretched hand for the away goal that would send Barcelona to the final.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Chelsea 1-1 Barcelona (agg 1-1) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8010840.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=6 May 2009 |accessdate=7 May 2009 }}</ref>

===Manchester United===
[[File:United V Celtic-4.jpg|thumb|alt=Celtic (foreground, in yellow) and Manchester United players (background, in red) and the match officials (in grey) line up prior to the group stage match between the two sides. Each player has a child mascot wearing a navy blue shirt standing in front of him, and a television camera crew is focusing on the Celtic players.|Manchester United and [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] line up prior to their Group E match at [[Old Trafford]] on 21 October 2008.]]
As the reigning champions of the UEFA Champions League, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] began their title defence at the group stage, for which they were given the top seed. This position amongst the top eight European clubs meant that they would avoid drawing former European champions [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]] and [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] until at least the first knockout round, although they were faced with the prospect of drawing [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] or [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]. Nevertheless, United ended up being drawn into Group E with two teams they had played against before: [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] (whom they had drawn in [[2005<U+2013>06 UEFA Champions League|2005<U+2013>06]]) and [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] ([[2006<U+2013>07 UEFA Champions League|2006<U+2013>07]]); and one they had not: [[AaB Football|Aalborg BK]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Man Utd to face Celtic in Europe |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7584644.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=28 August 2008 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref>

Two victories <U+2013> away to Aalborg and at home to Celtic <U+2013> and four draws were enough to secure passage to the knockout stage of the competition. Following a Celtic victory over Villarreal in the final group match, United went through as group winners.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Man Utd 2-2 Aalborg |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7763234.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=10 December 2008 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref> This meant that they would avoid Roma, Barcelona, Bayern Munich, [[F.C. Porto|Porto]] and [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in the first knockout round; however, their potential opposition still included Internazionale, [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]] and Real Madrid. The draw paired Manchester United with [[Jos<U+00E9> Mourinho]]'s Internazionale, but since United had won their group, they were rewarded by having the second leg at home.<ref>{{cite news |title=Man Utd to face Mourinho's Inter |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7790235.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=19 December 2008 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref>

United started the first leg the better of the two sides, and although Inter improved in the second half, neither side was able to find the net during the match, and United took a 0<U+2013>0 draw back to [[Old Trafford]]. The draw was also United's 20th match since their last defeat in the UEFA Champions League, breaking [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]'s 19-match record that had stood for 13 years.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Ashenden |title=Inter Milan 0-0 Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7904057.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=24 February 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref> The lack of an [[away goals rule|away goal]] at the [[San Siro]] meant that United could not afford to concede a goal in the event of a draw. A fourth-minute headed goal from [[Nemanja Vidi<U+0107>]], however, got the home side off to a good start, and [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] doubled United's lead four&nbsp;minutes into the second half. Shots from both [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi<U+0107>]] and [[Adriano Leite Ribeiro|Adriano]] hit the frame of the Manchester United goal in either half of the match, but they were unable to find the back of the net, and the 2<U+2013>0 result sent the English champions through to the next stage of the competition.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Man Utd 2-0 Inter Milan (agg 2-0) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7899577.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=11 March 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref>

The draw for the quarter-finals paired United with [[F.C. Porto|Porto]], against whom they had played in the first knockout round of the [[2003<U+2013>04 UEFA Champions League|2003<U+2013>04 competition]]. The draw also determined the semi-final pairings, with United or Porto drawn to play against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] or Villarreal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Liverpool draw Chelsea in Europe |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7954390.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=20 March 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref> The first leg of the quarter-final was played at Old Trafford, giving Porto the chance to put the pressure on Manchester United with an away goal. That away goal came in the fourth minute of the game, but [[Wayne Rooney]] equalised 10&nbsp;minutes later and [[Carlos T<U+00E9>vez]] gave United the lead in the 85th&nbsp;minute. However, with only one&nbsp;minute left in the game, United suffered a defensive lapse, allowing [[Mariano Gonz<U+00E1>lez|Mariano]] to score Porto's second away goal.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Man Utd 2-2 FC Porto |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7976964.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=7 April 2009 |accessdate=9 May 2009 }}</ref> Those away goals meant that United travelled to the [[Est<U+00E1>dio do Drag<U+00E3>o]] in [[Porto]] needing a win or a score-draw of 2<U+2013>2 or higher to remain in the competition. A 40-yard goal from Ronaldo in the sixth&nbsp;minute put United into the lead, and although both sides pressed for another goal, it proved to be the only one of the game, making Manchester United the first English side to win in Porto.<ref>{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Fletcher |title=FC Porto 0-1 Man Utd (agg 2-3) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7976970.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=15 April 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref>

[[File:Man Utd vs Arsenal 2009-04-29.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Wayne Rooney (in red) is shaping to kick the ball with an Arsenal player (in yellow) on either side of him. Cristiano Ronaldo, Carlos T<U+00E9>vez (both Manchester United) and Kolo Tour<U+00E9> (Arsenal) are looking on in the background.|[[Wayne Rooney]] and [[Mika<U+00EB>l Silvestre]] compete for the ball during the semi-final first leg between Manchester United and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].]]
Meanwhile, a 1<U+2013>1 draw in [[Villarreal]] and a 3<U+2013>0 win at the [[Emirates Stadium]] secured Arsenal's status as United's semi-final opponents.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Stevenson |title=Villarreal 1-1 Arsenal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7976997.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=7 April 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=Dawkes |title=Arsenal 3-0 Villarreal (agg 4-1) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7976998.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=15 April 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref> The draw had determined that United would play the first leg at home, and after Rooney, T<U+00E9>vez and Ronaldo had early chances, [[John O'Shea]] opened the scoring, firing home a [[Michael Carrick]] cross after Arsenal had failed to clear a corner. United continued to make chances throughout the game, but despite Arsenal making a couple of chances themselves, the match finished at 1<U+2013>0 and United travelled to the Emirates Stadium a week later needing only to avoid defeat to become the first defending champions to reach the final since Juventus in [[1997 UEFA Champions League Final|1997]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Man Utd 1-0 Arsenal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8010847.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=29 April 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref> Although Arsenal only needed to overturn a one-goal deficit, their chances of victory were drastically reduced within the first 11&nbsp;minutes of the match; [[Park Ji-Sung]] took advantage of a slip by [[Kieran Gibbs]] to double United's aggregate lead in the eighth&nbsp;minute, before Ronaldo fired home a 41-yard free kick in the 11th. With two away goals on the United scoreboard, Arsenal now had to score four goals to reach the final. However, it was United who scored the next goal, as they hit Arsenal on the break and Ronaldo scored within 15 seconds of Arsenal losing the ball at the other end of the pitch. 15&nbsp;minutes from time, Arsenal were awarded a [[penalty kick]] after [[Darren Fletcher]] brought [[Cesc F<U+00E0>bregas]] down in the [[penalty area]], a foul for which Fletcher was sent off <U+2013> despite replays showing that Fletcher had won the ball before making contact with F<U+00E0>bregas. [[Robin van Persie]] scored the penalty to make the score 3<U+2013>1, but it was not enough to prevent United from reaching the final unbeaten for the third time in their history.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Arsenal 1-3 Man Utd (agg 1-4) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8010853.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=5 May 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref>

==Pre-match==
===Venue===
[[File:2009 UCL Final Sponsor.jpg|thumb|A [[billboard]] in [[Rome]] advertising the 2009 UEFA Champions League Final, featuring the match logo and the tournament's six major sponsors.|alt=A billboard next to a road. The billboard is red and features a cartoon of a trophy with "MMIX" written on it. Below the trophy are the words "Roma Finale 2009". There are also two rows of three sponsor logos, followed by the words "Stadio Olimpico Roma 27 Maggio".]]
The [[Stadio Olimpico]] in [[Rome]] was selected as the venue for the 2009 UEFA Champions League Final at a meeting of the UEFA Executive Committee in [[Ljubljana]], [[Slovenia]], on 4 October 2006. The committee <U+2013> who decided the venue for the 2008 final and the [[2008 UEFA Cup Final|2008]] and [[2009 UEFA Cup Final]]s at the same meeting <U+2013> based its decision on a number of factors, including stadium capacity, safety and security facilities, and accessibility.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Chaplin |title=Moscow chosen for 2008 final |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=464106.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |location=[[Ljubljana]] |date=4 October 2006 |accessdate=12 May 2009 }}</ref>

Since [[1999 UEFA Champions League Final|1999]], the UEFA Champions League final has been given a unique visual identity in order to increase the marketing appeal of the event. Designed by [[London]]-based design and branding agency Radiant, the theme for the 2009 final was revealed on 25 October 2008, and it incorporated several typically [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] images; the logo was centred around an outline of the [[European Champion Clubs' Cup]], upon which was written "MMIX" <U+2013> "2009" in [[Roman numerals]]; around the base of the trophy was a stylised [[laurel wreath]], and in the background was a simplified image of the interior of the [[Colosseum]]. An alternative logo consisting of the UEFA Champions League logo surrounded by a laurel wreath was also released. The entire theme was based on a colour scheme of deep red and silver-white.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ancient and modern touch for 2009 logo |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=766089.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=25 October 2008 |accessdate=12 May 2009 }}</ref>

A trophy handover ceremony was held in Rome on 21 April 2009, at which [[Ole Gunnar Solskj<U+00E6>r]], representing Manchester United as the previous season's champions, returned the trophy to UEFA president [[Michel Platini]]. Platini then presented the trophy to [[Gianni Alemanno]], the [[List of mayors of Rome|Mayor of Rome]], that it might be put on display in and around the city until the day of the final. Also present at the ceremony were the president and vice-president of the [[Italian Football Federation]], Giancarlo Abete and [[Demetrio Albertini]], the ambassador for the final, [[Bruno Conti]], and Emilio Di Toro on behalf of the [[Italian National Olympic Committee]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Rome ready for trophy handover |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=822348.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=21 April 2009 |accessdate=2 February 2010 }}</ref>

===Ticketing===
[[File:Champions-League-2009-finale-ticket.jpg|thumb|left|A ticket for the 2009 UEFA Champions League Final, clearly showing the data chip as well as the holder's seat number]]
Although the usual capacity of the Stadio Olimpico is over 72,000, this was reduced to approximately 67,000 for the 2009 UEFA Champions League Final.<ref>{{cite news |title=Final in Rome will put fans first |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/keytopics/kind=64/newsid=800961.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=16 February 2009 |accessdate=13 October 2009 }}</ref> Approximately 10,000 tickets were made available to the general public, with recipients determined by a random ballot following an application period that ran from 2 March to 16 March 2009.<ref name="tickets">{{cite news |title=General ticket sales for Rome close |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/ticketing/newsid=810274.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=16 March 2009 |accessdate=12 May 2009 }}</ref> Each club was also allocated approximately 20,000 tickets for distribution to fans.<ref name="tickets"/> Manchester United chose to limit ticket applications to season ticket holders, with preference given to those who had attended more of the club's Champions League away fixtures that season.<ref>{{cite news |first=Stephen |last=Powell |title=Tickets for Rome |url=http://www.manutd.com/default.sps?pagegid={23A882F1-4E52-4C1A-816E-FB505E82E076}&newsid=6631792 |work=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=5 May 2009 |accessdate=12 May 2009 }}</ref> Barcelona, meanwhile, allotted 80% of their ticket allocation to fans, with the remaining 20% going to the club's corporate sponsors. Unlike United, however, Barcelona opened ticket applications to all 150,000 of their members.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tickets for Rome from Friday |url=http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/club/temporada08-09/05/n090506104891.html |work=FCBarcelona.cat |publisher=FC Barcelona |date=6 May 2009 |accessdate=12 May 2009 }}</ref> The remaining 17,000 tickets were retained by UEFA for the "European football family", which comprises UEFA itself, the local organising committee, UEFA's member associations, and its commercial partners.<ref name="tickets"/> Tickets for the 2009 final were similar to [[ATM card]]s, with an integrated chip storing the ticket holder's personal information in order to ensure that the ticket is being presented by its legitimate owner. As further security, tickets also had to be presented with an adequate form of photographic identification.<ref>{{cite news |title=Warning to ticketless United fans |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/8062934.stm |work=BBC News |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=22 May 2009 |accessdate=22 May 2009 }}</ref>

Despite only receiving 20,000 tickets for fans, it was expected that around 30,000 Manchester United fans would be travelling to Rome for the final, leading to police warning ticketless fans not to travel amidst fears of potential hooligans making the trip.<ref>{{cite news |title=Warning to ticketless United fans |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/8062934.stm |work=BBC News |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=22 May 2009 |accessdate=23 May 2009 }}</ref> Fans were also warned to avoid certain areas of the city that are known to be frequented by members of Rome's [[Ultras|Ultra]] fan groups.<ref>{{cite news |title=Man Utd fans given Rome warning |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/8058877.stm |work=BBC News |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=20 May 2009 |accessdate=23 May 2009 }}</ref> Despite Rome's reputation as a hotbed for knife-related crime, dubbed "Stab City" by some,<ref name="uefa_confident">{{cite news |first=Phil |last=Dawkes |title=Uefa confident of safe Euro final |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8034156.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=8 May 2009 |accessdate=23 May 2009 }}</ref> UEFA was confident that the 2009 final would pass without incident,<ref name="uefa_confident"/> but on the morning of the final, there were reports that a Manchester United fan had been stabbed in the leg the previous evening.<ref>{{cite news |title=United fan stabbed ahead of final |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/8069535.stm |work=BBC News |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=27 May 2009 |accessdate=27 May 2009 }}</ref> It was also expected that a similar number of Barcelona fans would be arriving in Rome in the lead-up to the match.<ref>{{cite news |title=United fans begin Rome journeys |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/8067693.stm |work=BBC News |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=26 May 2009 |accessdate=28 May 2009 }}</ref>

More than 3,000 Manchester United fans congregated just outside the city in a field that came to be known as "Fergie's Field".<ref name="ticketless">{{cite news |first1=John |last1=Hooper |first2=Owen |last2=Gibson |title=Ticketless Manchester United legion sets up camp on outskirts of Rome |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/may/26/champions-league-final-manchester-united |work=guardian.co.uk |publisher=Guardian News and Media |date=26 May 2009 |accessdate=27 May 2009 }}</ref> The venue provided ticketless fans with the opportunity to watch the match on a giant screen, and kept them away from the streets of Rome's city centre, although the alcohol ban that came into effect in the city at 17:00 ([[Central European Summer Time]]) on 26 May was still in force.<ref name="ticketless"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Rome puts alcohol limits on final |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8067274.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=25 May 2009 |accessdate=28 May 2009 }}</ref>

===Match ball===
[[File:Official match ball in Rome.jpg|thumb|upright|A giant replica of the ''adidas Finale Rome'' at the UEFA Champions Festival]]
The official [[Football (ball)|match ball]] for the 2009 Champions League final was the ''[[adidas]] Finale Rome''. Based on the "Starball" design that has been used for the Champions League final since [[2001 UEFA Champions League Final|2001]] and become synonymous with the UEFA Champions League, the ''Finale Rome'' was unveiled on 16 March 2009. The colour scheme was a traditional Roman [[burgundy (color)|burgundy]] with a gold border around the stars. The ball used the same panel configuration as the [[UEFA Euro 2008#Match ball|Adidas Europass]] and the [[Adidas Teamgeist]] before it, and the same thermal bonding process was used to adhere the panels to each other, while the surface of the ball featured the same "PSC-Texture" as was debuted with the Europass; the surface of the ball was covered with thousands of tiny pimples, which was designed to improve the grip between [[football boot|boot]] and ball.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iconic 'Finale Rome' set for ultimate stage |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=811193.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=16 March 2009 |accessdate=18 May 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=adidas Roma Champions League Final Ball Revealed! |url=http://www.soccerbible.com/news/general/archive/2009/03/16/football-news-adidas-roma-champions-league-final-ball-revealed-16-03-09.aspx |work=SoccerBible.com |publisher=SoccerBible |date=16 March 2009 |accessdate=18 May 2009 }}</ref>

===Officials===
[[File:Massimo Busacca.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Swiss referee [[Massimo Busacca]] at work]]
The [[referee (association football)|referee]] for the 2009 UEFA Champions League Final was [[Massimo Busacca]], representing the [[Swiss Football Association]].<ref name="referee"/> Having been on FIFA's list of internationally accredited referees since 1999,<ref>{{cite web |title=Switzerland - Men's Referees List |url=http://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/developing/refereeing/association=sui/peoplekind=ref.html |work=FIFA.com |publisher=F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Internationale de Football Association |accessdate=14 October 2009 }}</ref> Busacca had experience of officiating 32 UEFA Champions League matches, six of them during the 2008<U+2013>09 season, and most recently the second leg of Manchester United's quarter-final against [[F.C. Porto|Porto]] on 15 April 2009. He also took charge of the first leg of the semi-final between Manchester United and Barcelona in the [[2007<U+2013>08 UEFA Champions League|2007<U+2013>08 competition]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Paolo |last=Menicucci |title=Busacca relishes chance to referee final |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=833822.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=27 May 2009 |accessdate=27 May 2009 }}</ref> Busacca also refereed at both the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2008]], and took charge of the [[2007 UEFA Cup Final]] between [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] and [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] at [[Hampden Park]], [[Glasgow]], on 16 May 2007.<ref name="referee"/>

As usual, the referee was supported by assistant referees and a fourth official from the same country; in the 2009 final, Massimo Busacca was assisted by Matthias Arnet and Francesco Buragina, with Claudio Circhetta as the fourth official.<ref name="referee"/>

===Kits===
Having been designated as the official [[Home (sports)|"home" team]], Barcelona were given the first choice of kits for the final and opted to wear their traditional red and blue halved shirts. Since the Barcelona home kit clashed with both Manchester United's home and European away kits, the Red Devils wore their white domestic away kit for the first time in a European Cup final. They wore blue for their first European Cup final against [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in [[1968 European Cup Final|1968]], but wore red for both of their most recent finals in [[1999 UEFA Champions League Final|1999]] and [[2008 UEFA Champions League Final|2008]]. Manchester United had previously worn white against Barcelona in five matches, losing just one of them <U+2013> a 2<U+2013>0 defeat in 1984 <U+2013> while the only win in white came in the [[1991 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1991 Cup Winners' Cup Final]]. The other three matches finished in draws: two 3<U+2013>3 and one 0<U+2013>0. Barcelona, on the other hand, had won two of their five European Cup finals <U+2013> they wore orange for their win over [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] in [[1992 European Cup Final|1992]] but wore their usual blue and red stripes for their most recent win in [[2006 UEFA Champions League Final|2006]] against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. However, two of their European Cup final defeats came against teams wearing white <U+2013> against [[FC Steaua Bucure<U+015F>ti|Steaua Bucure<U+015F>ti]] in [[1986 European Cup Final|1986]] and against [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] in [[1994 UEFA Champions League Final|1994]].<ref name="kits">{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=Ashby |title=Red Devils will be all white on the night |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=833631.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Association |date=27 May 2009 |accessdate=27 May 2009 }}</ref>

===Opening ceremony===
{{Double image stack|right|FCB Mosaic.jpg|For Sir Matt mosaic.jpg|200|Fans of both teams form club-specific mosaics in the build-up to the match.}}
The 2009 UEFA Champions League Final officially opened with the opening of the UEFA Champions Festival at Rome's ''[[Arch of Constantine|Arco di Constantino]]'' and the ''Parco di Colle Oppio'' above the [[Colosseum]]. The Champions Festival was opened by former [[Italy national football team|Italian]] international [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] [[Luca Marchegiani]] on 23 May 2009 and ran until the afternoon on the day of the final, culminating with a football match between a European side coached by [[Ruud Gullit]] and an all-Italian team featuring [[Alessandro Costacurta]] and final ambassador [[Bruno Conti]]. Other attractions at the Champions Festival included appearances by representatives from both clubs ([[Bryan Robson]] and [[Ole Gunnar Solskj<U+00E6>r]] for Manchester United and [[Hristo Stoichkov]] for Barcelona), exhibitions featuring memorabilia from past UEFA Champions League tournaments and the [[European Champion Clubs' Cup]] on display.<ref>{{cite news |title=UEFA Champions Festival in Rome |url=http://www.uefa.com/multimediafiles/download/pressrelease/uefa/uefamedia/83/16/29/831629_download.pdf |format=PDF |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=20 May 2009 |accessdate=4 June 2009 }}</ref>

[[File:2009 Champions League Final opening ceremony.jpg|thumb|left|Dancers from the [[Rustavi Ensemble]] during the opening ceremony.]]
Immediately prior to the match itself came the opening ceremony for the final. The ceremony began with 64 members of the [[Rustavi Ensemble]] dance group performing a choreographed routine to a variation of the [[UEFA Champions League Anthem]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Rustavi female dancers' magnificent performance in Rome |url=http://www.ensemblerustavi.com/eng/?q=node/318 |work=ensemblerustavi.com |publisher=Rustavi Ensemble |date=29 May 2009 |accessdate=4 June 2009 }}</ref> At the culmination of the routine, the players emerged from the tunnel, accompanied by Italian [[tenor]] [[Andrea Bocelli]] singing ''Il Gladiatore'' <U+2013> a song based on ''Earth'' from the [[Gladiator (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the film ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]]'' <U+2013> before Bocelli sang backing vocals to the UEFA Champions League Anthem.<ref>{{cite news |first=Barry |last=Glendenning |title=Champions League final: Barcelona v Manchester United - as it happened |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/may/27/champions-league-final-barcelona-manchester-united |work=guardian.co.uk |publisher=Guardian News and Media |date=27 May 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2009 }}</ref>
{{-}}

==Match==
===Team selection===
[[File:Thierry Henry 2008.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Thierry Henry]] had suffered knee ligament damage and was a doubt for the final.]]
Two Barcelona players missed the final through [[Suspension (punishment)#Sport|suspension]]: right back [[Dani Alves]], who picked up his third yellow card of the tournament in Barcelona's semi-final second leg against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on 6 May 2009; and left back [[<U+00C9>ric Abidal]], who was [[Ejection (sports)#Association football (soccer)|sent off]] in the same game for a [[professional foul]] on [[Nicolas Anelka]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Chelsea 1-1 Barcelona (agg 1-1) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8010840.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=6 May 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref> Defender [[Rafael M<U+00E1>rquez]] also missed the match after he picked up a [[Knee #Disorders and injury|knee injury]] in the first leg of the semi-final, ruling him out for the rest of the season.<ref name="defence">{{cite news |title=Hiddink pays tribute to defence |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8021752.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=28 April 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref> Forward [[Thierry Henry]] and semi-final-winning midfielder [[Andr<U+00E9>s Iniesta]] were also doubts for the final; Henry damaged his right [[Posterior cruciate ligament|posterior knee ligament]] in Barcelona's 6<U+2013>2 league win over [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] on 2 May 2009, while Iniesta was discovered to have suffered a tear in his right thigh following Bar<U+00E7>a's 3<U+2013>3 draw with [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] on 10 May.<ref>{{cite news |title=Henry and Iniesta doubtful for United finale |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=828379.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=11 May 2009 |accessdate=18 May 2009 }}</ref> Both Henry and Iniesta returned to light training on 22 May, but they had not yet resumed training with the main squad and remained doubts for the final.<ref>{{cite news |title=Henry back with the first team squad |url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada08-09/05/n090522105175.html |work=fcbarcelona.com |publisher=FC Barcelona |date=22 May 2009 |accessdate=22 May 2009 }}</ref> [[Carles Puyol]], however, was available for selection after he served a one-match suspension in the semi-final second leg.<ref name="defence"/>  In all, FC Barcelona started with seven players who had come up through the youth system, of whom five were [[Catalonia|Catalans]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Rob |last=Draper |title=Guardiola's Barcelona are kings of the home-grown league |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1186902/Guardiolas-Barcelona-kings-home-grown-league.html |work=Daily Mail |publisher=Associated Newspapers |date=24 May 2009 |accessdate=6 June 2009 }}</ref>

[[File:Rio Ferdinand.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Rio Ferdinand]] had struggled with a calf injury since the semi-final second leg.]]
Manchester United's starting right-winger from the 2008 final, [[Owen Hargreaves]], missed the match as he was still in rehabilitation after a double knee operation to cure his [[tendinitis]] problems that had seen him play little part in the 2008<U+2013>09 Champions League campaign.<ref>{{cite news |first=Joe |last=Bernstein |title=United's Hargreaves undergoes second knee operation to save career |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1120906/Uniteds-Hargreaves-undergoes-second-knee-operation-save-career.html |work=Mail Online |publisher=Associated Newspapers |date=18 January 2009 |accessdate=14 February 2009 }}</ref> It had been expected that defender [[Wes Brown]] would also miss the match after suffering a recurrence of a foot injury,<ref>{{cite news |title=Brown set to miss Man Utd run-in |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/8039692.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=8 May 2009 |accessdate=9 May 2009 }}</ref> but he returned to training quicker than expected and was involved in United's match against [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] on 24 May,<ref>{{cite news |first=Ian |last=Hughes |title=Hull 0-1 Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8048308.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=24 May 2009 |accessdate=25 May 2009 }}</ref> although he picked up a slight knock during the game.<ref name="rio_on_course">{{cite news |first=Gemma |last=Thompson |title=Rio on course for Rome |url=http://www.manutd.com/default.sps?pagegid={F9E570E6-407E-44BC-800F-4A3110258114}&newsid=6633138 |work=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=24 May 2009 |accessdate=25 May 2009 }}</ref> [[Rio Ferdinand]] was also a doubt following a calf injury that has kept him out of the United side since the semi-final second leg against Arsenal; Alex Ferguson had said that Ferdinand may not start in Rome if he was not fit to play against Hull,<ref>{{cite news |title=Ferdinand faces 'toughest battle' |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/8060878.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=21 May 2009 |accessdate=22 May 2009 }}</ref> but he later admitted that Ferdinand was on course to recover in time to play in the match.<ref name="rio_on_course"/> Second-choice goalkeeper [[Ben Foster (footballer)|Ben Foster]] also missed the match after requiring surgery to repair a ruptured ligament in his right thumb in May 2009.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ben |last=Hibbs |title=Injury blow for Foster |url=http://www.manutd.com/default.sps?pagegid={F9E570E6-407E-44BC-800F-4A3110258114}&newsid=6632752 |work=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=18 May 2009 |accessdate=18 May 2009 }}</ref> On the other hand, following [[John O'Shea]]'s winning goal in Manchester United's semi-final first leg victory over [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], United manager [[Alex Ferguson]] suggested that the [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] utility player would be guaranteed a place in the starting line-up were United to reach the final.<ref>{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Bostock |title=O'Shea savours birthday gift |url=http://www.manutd.com/default.sps?pagegid={B4CEE8FA-9A47-47BC-B069-3F7A2F35DB70}&newsid=6631668&page=2 |work=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |page=2 |date=29 April 2009 |accessdate=29 April 2009 }}</ref> O'Shea's place in the team was confirmed at Manchester United's media one day the week before the final.<ref>{{cite news |title=O'Shea picked to start Euro final |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/8059180.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=20 May 2009 |accessdate=20 May 2009 }}</ref> Midfielder [[Park Ji-Sung]] was also promised a place in the team after he missed the [[2008 UEFA Champions League Final|2008 final]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Richard |last=Tanner |title=Un-Sung hero gets the nod |url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/99410/Un-Sung-hero-gets-the-nod |work=Daily Express |publisher=Northern and Shell Media Publications |date=7 May 2009 |accessdate=8 May 2009 }}</ref> Meanwhile, midfielder [[Darren Fletcher]] was forced to miss the final after picking up a [[Penalty card#Red card|red card]] in the second leg of the semi-final. While replays showed that Fletcher played the ball before felling [[Cesc F<U+00E0>bregas]] in the [[penalty area]], the [[UEFA]] appeals process only allows for cards to be rescinded in the case of mistaken identity.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fletcher red card to stand - Uefa |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8035053.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=6 May 2009 |accessdate=6 May 2009 }}</ref> Despite this, an appeal was submitted by Manchester United on "compassionate" grounds.<ref>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Bartram |title=UEFA to rule on Fletch |url=http://www.manutd.com/default.sps?pagegid={F9E570E6-407E-44BC-800F-4A3110258114}&newsid=6632212 |work=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=8 May 2009 |accessdate=8 May 2009 }}</ref>

[[File:Darren Fetcher.jpg|thumb|upright|Manchester United appealed against [[Darren Fletcher]]'s suspension, but the appeal was rejected.]]
Barcelona decided to appeal against the suspensions of Abidal and Alves after United lodged an appeal against Fletcher's red card. Barcelona manager [[Josep Guardiola|Pep Guardiola]] came out in support of overturning all three players' suspensions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barca to appeal Abidal and Alves suspensions |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=644765&cc=5901 |work=ESPN Soccernet |publisher=ESPN |date=9 May 2009 |accessdate=11 May 2009 }}</ref> The appeals were declared unsuccessful on 11 May, with UEFA saying in a statement that the appeals were not submitted within the required 24-hour deadline of the matches and that even if they had been submitted on time then "they would have been rejected as unfounded as there were no grounds for contesting the referees' original decisions."<ref>{{cite news |title=Man United, Barcelona protests not admitted |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/keytopics/kind=512/newsid=828892.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=11 May 2009 |accessdate=11 May 2009 }}</ref>

===Match summary===
====First half====
Barcelona kicked the match off, but Manchester United showed their intent from the outset, forcing goalkeeper [[V<U+00ED>ctor Vald<U+00E9>s]] to concede a throw-in after just 10 seconds. Further pressure on the attack resulted in [[Yaya Tour<U+00E9>]] fouling [[Anderson Lu<U+00ED>s de Abreu Oliveira|Anderson]] within [[Cristiano Ronaldo]]'s shooting range. Ronaldo fired the free kick directly at Vald<U+00E9>s, but the Spanish goalkeeper could only parry the ball and [[Gerard Piqu<U+00E9>]] did well to divert [[Park Ji-Sung]]'s follow-up effort over the bar. The resulting [[corner kick|corner]] was cleared, but only as far as [[Wayne Rooney]], whose snap-shot was wayward and went out for a [[goal kick]].

Both teams struggled to put a flowing move together in the opening exchanges, but it was United who had the better chances, both falling to Ronaldo. The first came in the seventh&nbsp;minute: having been played the ball by [[Michael Carrick]], Ronaldo turned away from Piqu<U+00E9> on the edge of the centre circle, before hitting a shot just wide from almost 40&nbsp;yards; the second saw the ball break to Ronaldo after Anderson and [[Patrice Evra]] had linked up well down the left flank. The Portuguese winger controlled the ball on the chest before hitting the ball just past the far post.

[[File:041 men at work UEFA 2009, Rome.jpg|thumb|left|Thierry Henry picks the ball out of the net after Barcelona's first goal.]]
However, despite United's early pressure, it was Barcelona who scored the first goal of the match. [[Edwin van der Sar]] cleared the ball downfield for Manchester United, but it was headed away by Barcelona's [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|midfield anchor]] [[Sergio Busquets]]. Carrick was first to the ball for Manchester United, but he could only head it as far as [[Xavi]], who passed to [[Andr<U+00E9>s Iniesta]]. The Manchester United defence backed away from the Spaniard, who <U+2013> after exchanging passes with [[Lionel Messi]] <U+2013> played the ball into the path of [[Samuel Eto'o]] in the Manchester United penalty area. [[Nemanja Vidi<U+0107>]] attempted to shepherd the Cameroonian striker towards the goal line, but Eto'o easily stepped inside him and toe-poked the ball past Van der Sar to make it 1<U+2013>0 to Barcelona inside 10&nbsp;minutes.<ref name="minute_by_minute">{{cite web |title=Minute-by-minute |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/fixturesresults/round=15280/match=302813/report=mbm.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=27 May 2009 |accessdate=30 May 2009 }}</ref>

The goal shifted the balance of the game in Barcelona's favour, as United had been on top in terms of shots and possession up to that point. Almost immediately after the restart <U+2013> Vidi<U+0107> gave away an unnecessary corner. In a rehearsed corner move, Xavi played the ball back to the edge of the penalty area towards Messi, but the tournament's top scorer was unable to make a proper connection. Nevertheless, Bar<U+00E7>a retained possession through some sharp inter-passing between Xavi and Iniesta. When United did managed to regain the ball, however, it was quickly given away by a poor pass from Carrick, while Anderson mis-timed a kick and completely missed the ball. It was now Barcelona's turn to pressurise the United players, forcing them into backward passes or long, hopeful balls forward.

The quality of the teams' passing remained the main difference between them; however, in the 16th&nbsp;minute, Barcelona lost the ball and [[Ryan Giggs]] sent a long ball forward to Ronaldo. Ronaldo's first touch took him inside Piqu<U+00E9> before going back outside the former Manchester United defender, who cynically blocked Ronaldo's run, earning himself the first [[Penalty card#Yellow card|yellow card]] of the match. Ronaldo shaped to take the free kick himself, but it was Giggs who shot for goal, only to curl the ball just over the bar.<ref name="minute_by_minute"/>

[[File:039 men at work UEFA 2009, Rome.jpg|thumb|Michael Carrick (background) watches as Lionel Messi shoots.]]
Barcelona responded almost immediately, [[Carles Puyol]] finding Eto'o with a long throw-in down the right wing. The Cameroonian then found Messi, who cut inside and hit a curling 25-yard shot that just shaved the top of the crossbar. A quick-passing move from United followed, culminating with a through-ball to Park in the inside right channel, only for Vald<U+00E9>s to cut out the pass, taking out the [[South Korea]]n in the process. The resulting throw-in eventually broke to Ronaldo, whose 30-yard shot went just wide. Vald<U+00E9>s' clash with Park, however, left him requiring treatment, and although the injury was not sufficient to necessitate a substitution, Vald<U+00E9>s chose to leave his next few goal kicks to Piqu<U+00E9>.

[[File:035 men at work UEFA 2009, Rome.jpg|thumb|left|Andr<U+00E9>s Iniesta (on the ground) is fouled by Anderson (number 8).]]
In the 22nd&nbsp;minute, a lofted through-pass from Carrick found Rooney on the left wing, but the Liverpudlian's cross was blocked by Tour<U+00E9> and went out for a corner kick. The corner, taken by Giggs, found Ronaldo, but the Portuguese got too far under the ball and headed over. Intricate passing from the Barcelona midfield got the Catalans moving upfield until a shoulder charge from Anderson sent Iniesta stumbling to the ground in the inside left channel 30&nbsp;yards from goal. The consequent free kick was taken by Xavi, who sent the ball just wide of the near post. Another free kick followed, as Messi was bundled over by a double-challenge from Vidi<U+0107> and Carrick, but it came to nothing.

[[File:2009 Champions League Final Xavi free kick.jpg|thumb|Xavi prepares to take the consequent free kick.]]
With ten&nbsp;minutes left until half-time, the Manchester United defence effectively switched off and allowed Tour<U+00E9> to dribble unopposed to within 15&nbsp;yards of their penalty area before slipping the ball out wide to Puyol, whose low cross was diverted behind by Vidi<U+0107>. The corner kick was taken short and the eventual cross was headed behind for another corner on the opposite side by Evra. The second corner was crossed in towards Piqu<U+00E9>, but he was unable to make contact with the ball.

With half-time fast approaching, Barcelona's confidence began to show: first, Messi attempted to flick a pass over the top of the United defence to [[Thierry Henry]], which [[Rio Ferdinand]] intercepted; Iniesta then tried an ambitious back-heel that Van der Sar collected; and finally Messi sped through three Manchester United defenders towards the by-line, only for his cut-back cross to be pounced upon by Van der Sar and then cleared by Vidi<U+0107>. On the stroke of half-time, Iniesta himself then attempted to flick the ball through to Henry, but it was just too high for the French striker, and referee [[Massimo Busacca]] took that cue to blow the whistle for the interval.

====Second half====
[[File:021 men at work UEFA 2009, Rome.jpg|thumb|left|Thierry Henry takes on Rio Ferdinand in the Manchester United penalty area.]]
After bringing on [[Carlos T<U+00E9>vez]] in place of [[Anderson Lu<U+00ED>s de Abreu Oliveira|Anderson]] at half time, Manchester United kicked off the second half in a different formation, with T<U+00E9>vez joining Ronaldo up front in a familiar 4-4-2. Both teams attempted to settle into their customary passing rhythms, but <U+2013> unlike the first half <U+2013> it was Barcelona who settled first; Manchester United's passes in their attacking third of the field failed to find their targets, and Iniesta came away with the ball before flicking a pass through to Xavi, who played a through-ball to Henry on the left wing. The French forward turned Ferdinand inside-out, but his shot from a narrow angle was straight at Van der Sar and ended up going out for a throw-in. Xavi then again passed the ball out to the left flank, where Henry nonchalantly left it for the on-rushing [[Sylvinho]]; the Brazilian full-back whipped in a cross for Eto'o, but it was caught on the edge of the six-yard box by Van der Sar.

[[File:019 men at work UEFA 2009, Rome.jpg|thumb|Carlos T<U+00E9>vez fouls Andr<U+00E9>s Iniesta on the edge of the Manchester United penalty area.]]
Pressure high up the pitch from Barcelona kept Manchester United in their own half, forcing them into attempting long balls downfield. A scrappy few moments in and around the centre circle followed, but Manchester United eventually came away with the ball. However, a lapse in communication between Giggs and Evra on the left wing allowed Eto'o to steal in and advance on the Manchester United goal. He cut in from the right wing and played a through-ball just out of reach of Messi, who went to ground after O'Shea had put his hand on Messi's shoulder. A period of sustained pressure from Barcelona followed, culminating with a run from Iniesta, who could only be stopped by a foul from T<U+00E9>vez on the edge of the Manchester United penalty area. The consequent free kick was taken by Xavi, who curled the ball around the defensive wall and onto the post with Van der Sar beaten.

[[File:Xavi al palo!.jpg|thumb|left|Xavi hits the free kick towards goal.]]
United responded with their first extended period of possession of the half, working the ball into wide areas to be crossed into the middle, but Rooney's first couple of attempted centres were well cleared by Piqu<U+00E9>. At the third attempt, though, Rooney's cross evaded the Barcelona defence as Tour<U+00E9> kicked at thin air; however, it also failed to find a Manchester United player in the penalty area, both Ronaldo and Park going close. After Ronaldo was called offside in the 59th&nbsp;minute <U+2013> despite appearing to be level with the last defender <U+2013> Giggs stole the ball mid-way inside the Barcelona half before playing the ball to Ronaldo on the left wing. The Portuguese forward stepped over the ball several times in an attempt to wrong-foot Puyol, before cutting inside and playing the ball across the edge of the area towards Carrick. A sliding challenge from Busquets prevented a shot, only for the English midfielder to slide the ball out for a Barcelona goal kick while attempting to play Rooney through. Rooney was again played down the right wing a few moments later, but his low cross was diverted behind by Piqu<U+00E9>, and the resulting corner came to nothing. A left-wing attack from Ronaldo followed, but after cutting inside, he gave the ball away cheaply. Barcelona immediately went on the attack down the other end, but Henry was unable to get past O'Shea and his shot was well saved by Van der Sar low at the near post.

In the 66th&nbsp;minute, Alex Ferguson completed his attacking quartet by bringing [[Dimitar Berbatov]] on in place of Park.<ref name="minute_by_minute"/> Ronaldo was penalised for a high elbow when challenging for a header with Puyol a minute later before Rooney forced another corner off Piqu<U+00E9> in the 69th&nbsp;minute. However, United's numbers up front in search of another goal left them wanting in defence; a weak clearance from Van der Sar was cut out by Puyol who played the ball to Eto'o on the right side of the penalty area. The ball broke to Xavi on the edge of the area, who crossed for Messi to send a looping header over the United goalkeeper and into the far side of the goal for a two-goal lead. Immediately after the goal, Henry was replaced by [[Seydou Keita (footballer)|Seydou Keita]], allowing Barcelona to adopt a more defensive stance.<ref name="minute_by_minute"/>

United responded to the goal immediately, as Giggs made a surging run through the Barcelona defence before playing the ball to Berbatov in the inside-right channel. The Bulgarian forward's low cross found Giggs in the centre, and the United captain's shot was deflected to Ronaldo on the far side of the goal, only for the Portuguese's shot to be blocked by Vald<U+00E9>s. The resulting corner reached Berbatov on the far side of the goal, but it was deemed to have crossed the goal line first and Barcelona were awarded a goal kick, from which they launched another attack. Messi played a through-ball to Puyol on the right flank, but as the Barcelona captain reached the goal line, he was fouled by Ronaldo, who <U+2013> despite going in two-footed <U+2013> escaped the referee's book. Puyol himself rose to head Xavi's free kick towards goal, but it was directly at Van der Sar, who claimed the ball easily.

Manchester United used their third and final substitute in the 75th&nbsp;minute, replacing Giggs with [[Paul Scholes]], who took over as team captain. Ronaldo and Scholes each received yellow cards in the 78th and 80th&nbsp;minutes, respectively; Ronaldo's yellow card was awarded for a robust shoulder-charge on Puyol as the Barcelona right back shepherded the ball out for a goal kick, while Scholes was booked for a late challenge on Busquets. While the referee played advantage after Scholes' foul, Iniesta cut inside from the left wing and hit a shot that was saved above the head of Van der Sar. An extended spell of Barcelona possession followed, as they strung a series of around 20 passes together, culminating with Puyol attempting to clip the ball over the onrushing Van der Sar, who blocked the shot. Both players went for the follow-up, but the Dutch goalkeeper was first to the ball and sent Puyol sprawling.<ref name="minute_by_minute"/>

In the 85th&nbsp;minute, Scholes clipped the ball over the top of the Barcelona defensive line to Rooney, who chested the ball down for T<U+00E9>vez, only to be given offside. Scholes then found Rooney again on the left wing with a raking ball from deep inside his own half, but Rooney's first touch was heavy, allowing Puyol to get back and put the ball out for a corner. Rooney took the corner short to T<U+00E9>vez, whose cross was just beyond the reach of Berbatov and diverted behind again by Puyol. Rooney also took the second corner, which was met by Berbatov, but he put the ball high over the crossbar.

As the match entered its closing stages, the referee allotted a minimum of three&nbsp;minutes of injury time. The first of these saw Van der Sar make a poor pass after the ball was played back to him by Ferdinand, allowing Iniesta to steal in and play the ball towards Messi in the United penalty area, only for Vidi<U+0107> to get there ahead of the Argentine and knock the ball out for a corner. Barcelona manager Josep Guardiola brought [[Pedro Rodr<U+00ED>guez Ledesma|Pedro Rodr<U+00ED>guez]] on for Iniesta in the second&nbsp;minute of added time, before Vidi<U+0107> was immediately shown a yellow card for a clash of heads with Messi when going for a header. That was to be the final act of the match, as referee Massimo Busacca blew for full time as soon as Xavi took the free kick.<ref name="minute_by_minute"/>

====Trophy presentation====
[[File:002 men at work UEFA 2009, Rome.jpg|thumb|Manchester United's players look on as their Barcelona counterparts receive their winners' medals.]]
At the final whistle, Barcelona manager [[Josep Guardiola]] offered his commiserations to each of Manchester United's players, while former Manchester United defender [[Gerard Piqu<U+00E9>]] fraternised with his erstwhile team-mates. Both teams then retreated to either end of the stadium to applaud their fans.

[[File:La cara de la derrota.jpg|thumb|left|[[Prince William of Wales|Prince William]] looks on as [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] receives his runners-up medal from [[UEFA]] President [[Michel Platini]].]]
While match referee [[Massimo Busacca]] and his assistants collected their mementoes of the final, the Barcelona team formed a [[guard of honour]] for the Manchester United players,<ref>{{cite video |people= |date=2009-05-27 |title=FC Barcelona UEFA Champions League Final 2009 Award Presentation |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gj9OyAs6RWs |format=FLV |medium=Television production |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=15 October 2009 |time=00:00:08 }}</ref> just as the English side had done for their opponents <U+2013> [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] <U+2013> in [[2008 UEFA Champions League Final|2008]]. Led by their manager, [[Alex Ferguson]], and team captain, [[Ryan Giggs]], the Manchester United team then ascended the specially constructed rostrum to collect their runners-up medals from [[UEFA]] president [[Michel Platini]] and secretary [[David Taylor (executive)|David Taylor]].<ref>FC Barcelona UEFA Champions League Final 2009 Award Presentation (00:00:15)</ref> Other dignitaries present included Manchester United chief executive [[David Gill (executive)|David Gill]]; [[The Football Association]]'s president [[Prince William of Wales|Prince William]], and chairman [[David Triesman, Baron Triesman|Lord Triesman]]; Barcelona president [[Joan Laporta]]; [[Juan Carlos I of Spain]]; [[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] president <U+00C1>ngel Mar<U+00ED>a Villar; and [[Prime Minister of Italy|Italian Prime Minister]] [[Silvio Berlusconi]]. Ferguson also collected a commemorative plaque from Platini, but immediately handed it to Giggs.<ref>FC Barcelona UEFA Champions League Final 2009 Award Presentation (00:00:31)</ref>

[[File:Celebrando la Copa de Campeones 2008-09.jpg|thumb|The Barcelona team, celebrating their victory with the [[European Champion Clubs' Cup]].]]
After offering his commiserations to Manchester United's players, Joan Laporta then joined the Barcelona team to lead them up the podium, closely followed by manager Guardiola.<ref>FC Barcelona UEFA Champions League Final 2009 Award Presentation (00:02:24)</ref> Laporta himself collected Barcelona's commemorative plaque before accepting a medal from Platini.<ref>FC Barcelona UEFA Champions League Final 2009 Award Presentation (00:02:38<U+2013>00:02:45)</ref> Once the entire Barcelona team had collected their medals, Platini made his way to the front of the podium to present [[Carles Puyol]] with the [[European Champion Clubs' Cup]].<ref>FC Barcelona UEFA Champions League Final 2009 Award Presentation (00:05:16)</ref> The Barcelona captain promptly held the trophy aloft with accompaniment from the [[UEFA Champions League Anthem]] and explosions of golden confetti, before leading his team on a lap of honour.<ref>FC Barcelona UEFA Champions League Final 2009 Award Presentation (00:05:28)</ref>
{{-}}

