==Reaction==
[[File:Lionel Messi 31mar2007.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Barcelona's [[Lionel Messi]] was voted as [[man of the match]] by ''uefa.com'' users.]]
During the match, ''uefa.com'' users were able to vote for their [[man of the match]]; the public vote went to the scorer of Barcelona's second goal, [[Lionel Messi]].<ref name="messi"/> The UEFA Technical Study Group, however, chose the man who provided the cross for Messi's goal, [[Xavi]], as their man of the match, citing his control of the tempo of the match as the reason for their decision.<ref name="xavi"/> Barcelona manager [[Josep Guardiola]] took the time to give special praise to Messi, whom he said he moved back into the midfield in order to increase the team's effectiveness when in possession of the ball.<ref name="praise">{{cite news |title=Guardiola praises Barcelona bravery |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8071196.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=27 May 2009 |accessdate=13 August 2009 }}</ref> Messi had been withdrawn from his usual right-wing role into a more attacking midfield position, while [[Samuel Eto'o]], who had started the match as Barcelona's lone centre-forward, was moved out to the right.<ref name="middle_men">{{cite news |first=David |last=Pleat |title=Middle men to the fore in dictating the rhythm with care |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/blog/2009/may/28/barcelona-manchester-united-david-pleat-chalkboard |work=guardian.co.uk |publisher=Guardian News and Media |date=28 May 2009 |accessdate=13 August 2009 }}</ref> Guardiola also lauded the bravery of his entire team, stating that he believed that his team's victory hinged on their hard work and propensity for taking risks in attack,<ref name="praise"/> but he admitted that although his side had had the best season in the history of the club, they were not yet the best Barcelona team.<ref name="guardiola_salutes"/>

{{multiple image
 | footer    = Barcelona's victory hinged on the performances of [[Andr<U+00E9>s Iniesta]] (left) and [[Xavi]] (right).<ref name="middle_men"/>
 | width     = 

 | image1    = Andr<U+00E9>s Iniesta - 001.jpg
 | width1    = 100
 | alt1      = Andr<U+00E9>s Iniesta

 | image2    = Xavi Hern<U+00E1>ndez - 001.jpg
 | width2    = 106
 | alt2      = Xavi
}}
In the Manchester United camp, manager [[Alex Ferguson]] admitted that his team had been beaten by the better side and that the game was all but lost after the first goal. He also paid tribute to Messi and the midfield partnership of Xavi and [[Andr<U+00E9>s Iniesta|Iniesta]], and expressed his regret at the unavailability of midfielder [[Darren Fletcher]], who was suspended for the match. He also lamented at his side's ineffectiveness when in possession. Nevertheless, Ferguson paid tribute to Guardiola's achievement of winning [[Treble (association football)#Continental trebles|the Treble]] in his first season of management.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barca were better side |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/8071178.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=28 May 2009 |accessdate=7 September 2009 }}</ref> Barcelona's victory also made Guardiola only the sixth man to win the competition as both a player and a manager, following in the footsteps of [[Miguel Mu<U+00F1>oz]], [[Giovanni Trappatoni]], [[Johan Cruyff]], [[Carlo Ancelotti]] and, most recently, [[Frank Rijkaard]], who also won the Champions League as Barcelona manager.<ref>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Haslam |title=Rookie coach enters illustrious company |url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/news/kind=1/newsid=834054.html |work=uefa.com |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |date=27 May 2009 |accessdate=8 September 2009 }}</ref>

[[File:Tevez throw.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Carlos T<U+00E9>vez]] chose to leave Manchester United at the end of his contract in June 2009.]]
The match turned out to be the last for [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] and [[Carlos T<U+00E9>vez]] as Manchester United players, as Ronaldo completed a world record <U+00A3>80&nbsp;million transfer to [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] on 1 July,<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo completes <U+00A3>80m Real move |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/8121951.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=1 July 2009 |accessdate=7 September 2009 }}</ref> while T<U+00E9>vez chose not to make his loan spell with the club permanent and joined their local rivals, [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Man Utd announce Tevez departure |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/8110740.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=20 June 2009 |accessdate=7 September 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Tevez completes move to Man City |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_city/8150002.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=14 July 2009 |accessdate=7 September 2009 }}</ref> After announcing his intention to leave Manchester United, T<U+00E9>vez criticised Ferguson's team selection for the 2009 Champions League final, saying that Ferguson should have included him in the starting line-up, with the rationale that the match was the only final that Manchester United had lost in his time at the club.<ref>{{cite news |title='Alex Ferguson should have started me against Barcelona,' says Carlos Tevez |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/jun/30/carlos-tevez-champions-league-final |work=guardian.co.uk |publisher=Guardian News and Media |date=30 June 2009 |accessdate=7 September 2009 }}</ref>

Television audiences for the final reached more than 10&nbsp;million in both Spain and the United Kingdom. 11.3&nbsp;million people watched the match on Spain's [[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3]] network <U+2013> the largest viewing figures for that station in the past year <U+2013> while another 600,000 watched on [[Canal+ Spain]]. In the United Kingdom, however, although the match received the highest ratings of any programme that evening, viewing figures were down by 1.5&nbsp;million on [[2008 UEFA Champions League Final|the previous year's final]], with just 9.6&nbsp;million watching on ITV1, although an additional 1.79&nbsp;million watched on [[Sky Sports|Sky Sports 1]]. Despite there being no Italian or French representative in the final, the figures were much the same in those two countries as they were in Spain and the United Kingdom, with Italy's [[Rai Uno]] garnering an average viewership of 9.63&nbsp;million and France's [[TF1]] receiving 8.25&nbsp;million. Only 6.55&nbsp;million people watched the match on Germany's [[Sat.1]] channel.<ref>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Clarke |title=European soccer final wins TV prize |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118004248.html?categoryid=3599&cs=1&nid=2565 |work=Variety |publisher=Reed Business Information |date=28 May 2009 |accessdate=8 September 2009 }}</ref>

[[File:Etoo Joan Gamper Trophy 2008.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Samuel Eto'o]] scored the opening goal in the 10th&nbsp;minute of the game.]]
In the United Kingdom, [[bookmaker]]s made a profit out of patriotic Britons placing bets on a Manchester United victory. [[William Hill (bookmaker)|William Hill]] reported two bets of around <U+00A3>20,000 placed on Manchester United, while [[Paddy Power]] received one of <U+00A3>5,500 and [[Ladbrokes]] one of <U+00A3>3,000. Ladbrokes also took a bet of <U+00A3>10,000 on a Barcelona win, but bookmakers reported that most of the money was put on Manchester United. Extrabet.com paid out <U+00A3>12,000 to a <U+00A3>3,000 bet on Samuel Eto'o to score the first goal at 4<U+2013>1.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dan |last=Roebuck |title=Barcelona triumph keeps the bookies happy |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/may/28/champions-league-final-betting |work=guardian.co.uk |publisher=Guardian News and Media |date=28 May 2009 |accessdate=8 September 2009 }}</ref>

==Rewards==
Both teams received significant financial rewards for reaching the Champions League final. However, despite losing the match, it was Manchester United who earned the most money from their 2008<U+2013>09 Champions League campaign, receiving [[Euro|<U+20AC>]]38.281&nbsp;million compared to Barcelona's <U+20AC>30.968&nbsp;million. All 32 teams in the group stage of the competition received <U+20AC>3&nbsp;million for taking part in the competition and <U+20AC>2.4&nbsp;million for their participation in the group stage matches, as well as further bonuses based on their performances in each match (<U+20AC>600,000 for each win and <U+20AC>300,000 for each draw). For their four wins and one draw, Barcelona received a performance bonus of <U+20AC>2.7&nbsp;million, while Manchester United earned <U+20AC>2.4&nbsp;million for their two wins and four draws. Both teams then also received a total of <U+20AC>7.7&nbsp;million for their participation in the rounds leading up to the final; however, Barcelona received a win bonus of <U+20AC>7&nbsp;million for winning the final, while Manchester United received <U+20AC>4&nbsp;million for finishing as runners-up. The biggest difference between the teams' financial rewards came as a result of their share of the market pool, based on the value of the television market in their home countries. As the most successful of the English teams in the competition, Manchester United received the greatest share (<U+20AC>18.781&nbsp;million) of approximately <U+20AC>55.5&nbsp;million reserved for the English teams. However, although Barcelona were the most successful of the Spanish teams in the competition, they had finished in third place in [[La Liga]] the [[La Liga 2007<U+2013>08|previous season]], and so received the second-smallest share of the <U+20AC>33.8&nbsp;million given to the four Spanish clubs, taking home <U+20AC>8.168&nbsp;million.<ref name="distribution"/>

In addition to receiving almost <U+20AC>31&nbsp;million in prize money, as winners of the UEFA Champions League, Barcelona competed in the [[2009 UEFA Super Cup]], in which they beat [[2008<U+2013>09 UEFA Cup]] winners [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]] 1<U+2013>0 at [[Stade Louis II]] in [[Monaco]] on 28 August 2009,<ref name="super_cup"/> and in the [[2009 FIFA Club World Cup]] in [[Abu Dhabi]].<ref name="club_world_cup"/>

